{"type":"message","id":"0e337067","parentId":"df948e26","timestamp":"2026-04-23T17:43:26.192Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The issue is that the user is running `yarn dev` locally and it's still hitting the \"too many open files\" error. This is likely because there are many ts-node-dev processes still running on the server, and each one creates file watchers. The user is trying to run it on their local machine, but the issue is on the server side with multiple node processes competing for file watchers.\n\nWait, actually looking at the path - `root@atu-ahv-ai006:~/.openclaw/workspaces2/projects/ahv-qlhv-be#` - the user IS on the server. They're running the command on the server.\n\nThe issue is that `ts-node-dev` uses `chokidar` to watch files, and it opens many file watchers. \n\nSo the user ran `yarn dev` from their terminal, and I also started a process earlier that seems to have exited, but there are still many node processes running from the earlier executions. With `ts-node-dev` trying to watch the entire project directory, we're hitting the system limit on file watchers.\n\nThe solution is to either switch to `ts-node` for a one-shot run, use `--respawn` and `--exit-child` flags with `ts-node-dev`, or increase the system's `fs.inotify` limits. The real fix is probably killing all the lingering node processes and restarting fresh. Let me check what processes are currently running to identify the culprits.","thinkingSignature":"50a4a2eb53549cf9cd2755f9fe30f912f07965706c2ecacb0f68ecdd01c9b6ca"},{"type":"text","text":"Lỗi vẫn còn — có quá nhiều watcher processes trên server. Mình kill triệt để hết rồi bạn chạy lại.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_u9z1n3h04fcx_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"ps aux | grep -E \"ts-node|node.*ahv|tsx|watch\" | grep -v grep | awk '{print $2, $11}' | head -20","yieldMs":5000,"timeout":10}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"ahvholding","model":"AHV-Holding-DEV","usa