{"type":"message","id":"729cf104","parentId":"d04a4ba5","timestamp":"2026-04-23T18:10:44.379Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see the data clearly. The `teacher_id` in `coursestudents` for the teacher account is `ObjectId('69e8333ddbb6750f8166f05e')` which matches the `_id` of `teacher@qlhv.vn`. And the database HAS many overdue ongoing courses for this teacher.\n\nBut the issue is that the backend code uses `new mongoose.Types.ObjectId(teacherId)` where `teacherId` comes from the JWT token. Let me check if the JWT token has the correct `id` format. \n\nActually, the bigger issue is: the `teacher_id` in `coursestudents` is an ObjectId, but the `_id` of the `users` collection might be stored differently. Let me check what format the `_id` is in the `users` collection.\n \nI found the real problem—there's a collection name mismatch. The MongoDB collection is `courses`, but the aggregate pipeline is looking up `courseinfos`, which doesn't exist. That's why the query isn't returning any results even though the data is there. The issue is that `teacher_id` is stored as a string in the JWT payload, but the backend tries to convert it to an ObjectId for database queries. However, the `_id` field in the `users` collection is actually stored as a string, not an ObjectId, so this conversion might be causing a mismatch when trying to find the teacher's courses. which IS an ObjectId. But the `_id` in the `users` collection might be stored as a string (not ObjectId), while `teacher_id` in `coursestudents` is an ObjectId.\n\nActually, looking at the MongoDB data, the `_id` of the teacher user was shown as `\"69e8333ddbb6750f8166f05e\"` (string-like) but when I used `ObjectId(\"69e8333ddbb6750f8166f05e\")` in the query, it found the user. So the `_id` is indeed an ObjectId.\n\nThe real problem is that the `courseinfos` collection doesn't exist—it's actually called `courses`. Once I fix that, the query should work. Let me restart the backend and test it. But I should also verify what format the JWT token's user ID is in and whether it matches what the backend expects.\n\nThe `_id` field in MongoDB is always an ObjectId, even though it might display as a hex string in the shell. When Mongoose returns documents, it converts these to ObjectId instances, so the JWT payload's `id` field should already be in the correct format.\n\nHowever, there's a mismatch in the collection naming: the `$lookup` is referencing `courseinfos` when it should be `courses`, and the MongoDB data confirms the collection is `courses`. I should restart the backend and have the user test the fix, though I could also add debug logging to verify the user ID format is correct.","thinkingSignature":"6688625d061a2bc6ca4841ef44677773376203433f9f16b10f106af2a6eea6b2"},{"type":"text","text":"Database **có rất nhiều dữ liệu** — 13 khóa ongoing quá hạn cho teacher này. Lỗi đã fix rồi (`courseinfos` → `courses`). Mình restart BE để áp dụng:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_b5m7zza34cy7_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"kill $(ps aux | grep \"ts-node-dev.*ahv-qlhv-be\" | grep -v grep | awk '{print $2}') 2>/dev/null\nsleep 1\nnohup npx ts-node-dev --transpile-only -r tsconfig-paths/register --exit-child src/index.ts > /tmp/ahv-be.log 2>&1 &\necho \"BE restarting...\"\nsleep 6\ncurl -s -o /dev/null -w \"BE: %{http_code}\" http://localhost:5002/api/v1/health","workdir":"/root/.openclaw/workspaces2/projects/ahv-qlhv-be","yieldMs":20000,"timeout":30}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"ahvholding","model":"AHV-Holding-DEV","usage":{"input":41537,"output":869,"cacheRead":71934,"cacheWrite":1502,"totalTokens":115842,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776967824622,"responseId":"06399393913ad90c02e93c5bcf884d67"}}
