{"type":"message","id":"51f1e2e8","parentId":"9d1d8244","timestamp":"2026-04-23T18:37:36.653Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user wants to follow a strict process for each branch:\n1. Checkout the branch\n2. Check lint\n3. Test / build\n4. Push\n5. Create merge request\n6. Wait for merge to complete\n7. Then checkout develop, pull new code\n8. Checkout next branch, merge with develop (resolve conflicts if any)\n9. Repeat\n\nThis is a sequential process. I need to do them one by one. Let me start with the BE branches first, then FE branches.\n\nLet me start by going through each branch systematically. I'll need to:\n\n\n1. For each BE branch: lint → build → push → create MR → wait for merge → pull develop → next branch\n2. For each FE branch: lint → build → push → create MR → wait for merge → pull develop → next branch\n\nSince some branches fix the same issues, I should consolidate them first before pushing. Let me check the current state of both repos and then begin the workflow.\n\nLooking at the BE branches, I see there are multiple commits addressing similar problems. I need to squash them into single, meaningful commits per branch to keep the history clean before following the standard push and merge process.\n\nNow I'm realizing I should do a soft reset and recommit with proper messages to consolidate the duplicate work. But first, let me actually start pushing and see what conflicts come up, then handle the consolidation as I go.\n\nFor the workflow, I need to get the GitLab remote URL, create MRs using the glab CLI if available, and establish a waiting mechanism to check when branches merge. Let me begin by checking the remote and whether glab is installed.","thinkingSignature":"56ceb852b674f48e686b8a5da65ccb472c66b7bc1cbaf8064184bd4fa930e8e0"},{"type":"text","text":"Rõ rồi. Mình sẽ làm tuần tự từng branch: lint → build → push → tạo MR → đợi merge → checkout develop pull → branch tiếp theo.\n"},{"type":"toolCall"